{
    "analysis": "Previous step: Executor loaded metric.csv and trace.csv and returned compact summaries. Key findings from that output: metric.csv covers timestamps from 2020-05-27 01:30 to 2020-05-27 02:30 (Asia/Shanghai), and contains many cmdb_id values including node-level (os_00x), container-level (docker_00x), db_00x and osb_001. Many KPIs are available (CPU, Memory, Disk_io_util, Network send/recv, Agent_ping, and business KPIs like app.succee_rate/app.avg_time). trace.csv covers 2020-05-27 02:00 to 02:29 (Asia/Shanghai) and most trace rows are for docker_001 (various trace.self.* and trace.from_os_022.*). This narrows the trace-enabled scope to docker_001 and interactions from os_022. No conclusions yet on root cause. Next we must run metric-based anomaly detection using global thresholds (computed over full series) and then extract anomalies within the incident window (2020-05-27 02:00 to 02:30).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, do the following (keep outputs compact and bounded):\n1) For each group (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 thresholds using the full available series in metric.csv. Also record total count of points per group.\n2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window: 2020-05-27 02:00:00 CST through 2020-05-27 02:30:00 CST (inclusive start, inclusive end).\n3) Using the thresholds from step 1, detect anomalies in the filtered window where either value >= P95 (high anomaly) OR value <= P5 (low anomaly). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) that has >=1 anomaly point in the window, produce one row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_count, p95, p5, window_total_rows, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window.\n4) Return up to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc, then by earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc. Present results as a compact CSV-like table and nothing else."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric analysis we found many DB-related KPIs (db_001, db_002, db_003, etc.) and some node/container KPIs flagged as anomalous across the whole incident window. Notably tnsping_result_time for db_001/db_002 had max=10 and min=0 across the window, suggesting intermittent DNS/TNS or network reachability latency to DBs. Trace data indicates docker_001 has traces labeled trace.from_os_022.remoteprocess.* and several self.* traces during the incident window, implying docker_001 communicates with os_022 and may be involved in the fault path. To localize the root cause we need to (1) confirm whether tnsping spikes coincide with any trace latency spikes, and (2) find the earliest timestamp when these spikes start within 2020-05-27 02:00–02:30 CST. This will help determine the root cause component (DB vs network vs container) and the exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) For trace.csv: compute global P95 for each of these trace groups using the full trace.csv series: (docker_001, trace.from_os_022.remoteprocess.duration_mean), (docker_001, trace.from_os_022.remoteprocess.duration_p95), (docker_001, trace.self.local.duration_mean), (docker_001, trace.self.local.duration_p95). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2020-05-27 02:00:00 CST through 2020-05-27 02:30:00 CST and, for each of the above groups, return rows where value >= global_P95. For each matching group return: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_count, global_p95, window_row_count, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Limit to top 20 rows.\n\n2) For metric.csv: for tnsping_result_time for cmdb_id in (db_001, db_002, db_003) compute global P95 using the full metric series, then filter to the incident window and return rows where value >= global_P95 (or value>0 if P95==0). For each db return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_count, global_p95, window_row_count, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Limit to top 20 rows.\n\nReturn results as compact CSV-like tables and nothing else."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step summary: metric and trace analyses indicate tnsping_result_time spikes (value=10) on db_003 starting at 2020-05-27 02:00:00 CST, then on db_002 (02:02) and db_001 (02:03). Trace latency anomalies on docker_001 appear later (first around 02:06–02:08). Network-related KPIs on os_022 (Agent_ping, ICMP_ping, Incoming/Outgoing traffic) and some CPU/MEM metrics on DB hosts were also flagged, but many MEM_Total entries are constant and coincide with thresholds (likely not causal). The ordering (DB tnsping spikes → later trace latency on docker_001) suggests a DB reachability/latency problem beginning with db_003. However, to confidently localize the root cause we need to identify the very first anomalous metric event and quantify its severity (deviation from the global threshold) across all candidate groups.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, compute global P95 and P5 for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the full series. Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2020-05-27 02:00:00 CST through 2020-05-27 02:30:00 CST. For each group that has >=1 anomaly in the window (value>=P95 OR value<=P5; special-case tnsping_result_time: if global P95==0 treat any value>0 as anomaly), find the earliest anomaly point in the window and record its value. For each such group produce one compact row with these columns: cmdb_id,kpi_name,global_count,global_p95,global_p5,earliest_anomaly_timestamp,earliest_value,absolute_deviation,relative_deviation_pct. Compute absolute_deviation as (earliest_value - global_p95) when earliest_value>=global_p95, otherwise (global_p5 - earliest_value). Compute relative_deviation_pct = absolute_deviation / (global_p95 if global_p95>0 else 1) * 100. Sort rows by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending and return up to top 20 rows as a CSV-like table and nothing else."
}

